---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ColorPalette from '../../components/ColorPalette.jsx';
import RelatedTools from '../../components/RelatedTools.astro';
import PromoBanner from '../../components/PromoBanner.jsx';
---

<Layout
  title="Color Palette Generator Online: Free | PixMidas"
  description="Color Palette Generator Free | Extract Colors from Any Image - PixMidas"
  canonical="https://www.pixmidas.com/tools/color-palette/"
>
  <div class="tool-page">
    <div class="tool-header">
      <a href="/categories/image-tools/" class="back-link">← Image Tools</a>
      <h1 class="tool-title">Color Palette Generator</h1>
      <p class="tool-subtitle">Upload any image and instantly extract the 6 most dominant colors. Get HEX and RGB values, copy with one click, or download the palette as a PNG.</p>
    </div>

    <ColorPalette client:load />


    <div class="promo-wrap">
      <PromoBanner client:load excludeSlug="color-palette" />
    </div>

    <section class="seo-content">
      <p>Color palettes are the foundation of every consistent design system, brand identity, and visual project. When you're building a website, designing marketing materials, or matching UI elements to a brand photograph, you need the actual HEX and RGB values from your real assets, not an approximation you've eyeballed. This tool analyzes every pixel in your uploaded image and returns the six most visually distinct dominant colors with precise HEX and RGB codes ready to copy directly into CSS, Figma, Sketch, or any design tool. All processing runs in your browser using the Canvas API, your image is never uploaded to any server.</p>

      <h2>How to use</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Upload any image, a photo, logo, screenshot or graphic.</li>
        <li>The tool analyzes the image and extracts the 6 most dominant colors automatically.</li>
        <li>Click any color swatch to copy its HEX code, or download the palette as a PNG reference sheet.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Tips for best results</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Use clean, high-contrast images for branding.</strong> Product photos with simple backgrounds yield the most actionable palettes, the extracted colors represent actual brand tones rather than ambient lighting artifacts or background noise from complex scenes.</li>
        <li><strong>Fine-tune shades with the color picker.</strong> Once you have your palette, paste any HEX value into the <a href="/tools/color-picker/" class="tool-suggestion">color picker</a> to adjust hue, saturation or brightness, useful for creating lighter hover states, darker shadow tones or accessible contrast variants from your extracted base colors.</li>
        <li><strong>Apply palette colors to watermarks.</strong> When adding branded text overlays to images, copy the HEX values from your extracted palette into the <a href="/tools/image-watermark/" class="tool-suggestion">image watermark tool</a> to keep watermark colors on-brand across all output files.</li>
        <li><strong>Check small-scale legibility.</strong> Extract colors from your logo, then test how they appear in compact contexts like a <a href="/tools/qr-code/" class="tool-suggestion">QR code</a>, some colors that look vibrant at full size lose distinction at small dimensions, and verifying this early prevents brand inconsistency in print and digital outputs.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why use PixMidas</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>100% private.</strong> Color extraction runs in your browser via the Canvas API, your image is never uploaded.</li>
        <li><strong>Six distinct colors.</strong> The algorithm avoids near-identical shades, you get the most visually distinct dominant colors in the image.</li>
        <li><strong>No account needed.</strong> Free, instant, no usage limits.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

      <h3>How does color extraction work?</h3>
      <p>The tool samples thousands of pixels from the image and groups them by visual similarity using a color quantization algorithm. Colors that are perceptually similar are merged into clusters, and the center of each cluster becomes the returned color. This gives you the most representative distinct colors, not just the most frequent single pixel value. The approach is similar to the median cut and k-means clustering techniques used in professional image processing libraries.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between dominant and accent colors?</h3>
      <p>Dominant colors cover the most visual area in the image. Accent colors appear less frequently but stand out because of contrast or saturation. For branding work, dominant colors typically become background or base colors, and accent colors become highlight or call-to-action colors. Understanding this distinction helps you assign extracted colors to the right roles in a design system rather than using them interchangeably.</p>

      <h3>What format are the color values in?</h3>
      <p>Both HEX (#rrggbb) and RGB (r, g, b) values are shown for each extracted color. Click any swatch to copy the HEX value to your clipboard. For CSS use, HEX is typically the most convenient format. For design tools that accept HSL values, paste any HEX code into the <a href="/tools/color-picker/" class="tool-suggestion">color picker</a>, it shows the same color simultaneously in HEX, RGB and HSL so you can copy the format your tool requires.</p>

      <h3>What can I use an extracted palette for?</h3>
      <p>Matching brand colors across a website, presentation or printed materials. Building a cohesive color scheme from a hero photograph. Checking what colors a reference design actually uses. Creating consistent UI themes in Figma or Sketch. Identifying dominant colors for accessibility documentation, knowing your exact foreground and background HEX values makes it straightforward to test contrast ratios against WCAG accessibility standards before publishing.</p>

      <h3>How many colors are extracted?</h3>
      <p>Always six. The algorithm returns six visually distinct dominant colors regardless of image complexity. Simple images like logos return the exact colors used. Complex photographs return the most representative color clusters from the image. Six colors gives you enough variety for a complete design palette, primary, secondary, accent and neutral tones, without so many near-identical options that the palette becomes hard to apply consistently.</p>

      <div class="related-tools">
        <p>Related tools</p>
        <div class="related-tools-links">
          <a href="/tools/color-picker/">Color Picker</a>
          <a href="/tools/image-watermark/">Image Watermark</a>
          <a href="/tools/qr-code/">QR Code Generator</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <RelatedTools slugs={["color-picker", "image-info", "compress-image"]} />
  </div>
</Layout>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebApplication",
  "name": "Color Palette Generator",
  "url": "https://www.pixmidas.com/tools/color-palette/",
  "applicationCategory": "MultimediaApplication",
  "operatingSystem": "Any",
  "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript",
  "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0", "priceCurrency": "USD" },
  "description": "Extract dominant colors from any image instantly. Get HEX and RGB values with one click. Free, no login.",
  "provider": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "PixMidas", "url": "https://www.pixmidas.com" }
}
</script>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I extract colors from an image?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Upload your image and the tool instantly extracts the 6 most dominant colors. Each color is shown as a swatch with HEX and RGB values. Click any swatch to copy the HEX code to your clipboard." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What can I use an extracted color palette for?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Color palettes are used in branding, web design, presentations and marketing to maintain visual consistency. Extracting colors from a logo or photo ensures all your design elements use matching colors in CSS, Figma, Sketch, or Photoshop." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between HEX and RGB color codes?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "HEX is a six-digit code like #3a86ff used in CSS and design tools. RGB uses three values 0–255 like rgb(58, 134, 255). Both represent the same color and are accepted by all major design and web tools." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are images uploaded to a server?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Color extraction runs entirely in your browser using the Canvas API. Your image is never uploaded or sent anywhere." }
    }
  ]
}
</script>
